<subSubSection pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1436,1410,1698]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,328,1522,1548]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Bosmans &amp; Cardoso &amp; Crespo, 2010" authorityName="Bosmans &amp; Cardoso &amp; Crespo" authorityYear="2010" box="[341,638,1523,1548]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Pelecopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monsantensis" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[341,638,1523,1548]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Pelecopsis monsantensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[651,797,1522,1548]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
is distinghuished from other 
<taxonomicName box="[1171,1394,1522,1548]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Pelecopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1171,1296,1523,1548]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Pelecopsis</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
by combined characters of the shape of the prosoma and the structure of the male palp. The prosoma has a cephalic tubercle with a large sulcus behind the eyes, generally much smaller in other species and the palpal tibia has a twisted base, straight in all other species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="45" lastPageNumber="46" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="description">
